{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's Heart (from *Diwan-e-Ghalib*, Ghazal 33):**  \nIt is a heart, not stone and brick, that fills with pain;  \nWe'll weep a thousand times—why should a soul be slain?[^1]\n\n**Iqbal's Heart (from *Bang-e-Dara Part 1*, \"Dil\"):**  \nAt times it seems the Divine Throne, at times the Kaaba's shrine;  \nMy God, whose destination is this, this humble abode of the heart?[^2]\n\n**Ghalib's Heart:**  \nNo temple here, no holy shrine, no door, no sacred fane;  \nWe sit upon the public road; why should a stranger then complain?[^3]\n\n**Iqbal's Heart:**  \nThe plea, 'Show me Thyself!' is the headline of the heart's tale;  \nFor it, the gallows and the rope are but a childish game.[^4]  \nIf the realm of eternity marks the measure of the heart,  \nO Lord, what must be the wine of this brimming chalice?[^5]\n\nIn this staged exchange, Ghalib's heart asserts its fleshy vulnerability against lifeless brick and stone, rejecting sanctity for raw emotion on the open road. Iqbal's heart counters by embracing its objectified grandeur as a cosmic dwelling—throne, shrine, abode—yet pulsing with divine longing, where pain is a mere prelude to eternity's feast.\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/33-dil-hi-to-hai-na-sang-o-khisht-dard-se-bhar-na-aay/translation/#p-d9d50d).\n\n[^2]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/18-dil/translation/#p-1bdee7).\n\n[^3]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/33-dil-hi-to-hai-na-sang-o-khisht-dard-se-bhar-na-aay/translation/#p-3089fc).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/18-dil/translation/#p-26e13d).\n\n[^5]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 1*, [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-1-55b25c/18-dil/translation/#p-4cc8e8).",
